Bought a boat after tenth grade
"I think there are not many fishermen who work in the kindergartens of the country," says Axel Örn Guðmundsson, who engages in coastal fishing in the summers but studies psychology at the University of Iceland during the winter."
Beach fishing is a very convenient summer job when you are studying.
If fishing goes well, it's possible to have a good income and I think it's great to be able to avoid taking student loans.
"The earnings also sustain me well into the winter," says Axel Örn Guðmundsson, a 25-year-old psychology student, who engages in coastal fishing in the summer just as in previous summers.
Axel had just docked at the pier in Tálknafjörður when a journalist caught up with him late in the evening at the beginning of the week.
"The winter when I was in tenth grade, I obtained my boat captain's license for boats that are under twelve meters long and I bought my own boat the summer after I finished elementary school."
I have gone sea angling in my boat all summers since then.
I bought the used boat from my acquaintance, Hartmann Jónsson, and I named the boat after him.
Hartmann had grown up when I bought the boat and had stopped going to sea and he was very content when he saw that the boat bore his name.
Hartmann died a few years after I took over the boat," says Axel, adding that he bought the boat for three million.
"I made a deal with Hartmann to pay half, one and a half million, at the beginning of summer, and the other half at the end of summer when I would have finished fishing."
I therefore owned the boat debt-free at the end of that first summer of mine on it.
But how could a boy have one and a half million to pay out for a boat when he had just finished primary school?
"I had been saving and collecting money, I had been working with dad at sea when I was a boy, I spent all summers fishing with him and got my share."
I also put my confirmation money into my boat fund.
Axel was born in Ísafjörður, where all of his mother's family is from, but he has lived in Kópavogur since he was a boy.
"I am allowed to fish here in the western area because I have a legal residence with my grandmother in Ísafjörður."
I learned about these areas here in the west from rowing with Dad.
I move between the fjords depending on how I feel, because this fishing area covers all of the Westfjords.
Although I like being in the west the best, I have also fished around the Snæfellsnes peninsula and elsewhere.
I have also fished in the south, mainly for lumpfish," says Axel, who always rows out alone early in the morning and says he sometimes talks to the seagulls and sings to the sky, in solitude for hours on end out on the open sea.
"The internet connection out at sea is good, so I can make calls, listen to podcast episodes, and music."
I have no problem being alone on a boat.
"Of course, I try to avoid getting into danger, but certainly, there have been times when something has been off with the weather, but never a great danger," says Axel, who is lucky in that he never gets seasick.
He says the length of the workday depends on how the fishing goes each time.
"In the shore fishing, I'm never more than 14 hours at a time fishing, but I have also been fishing in other systems, like the lease quota, and then I've been continuously for one and a half days baiting at sea fishing."
The arrangement in coastal fishing, he says, is such that he is allowed to fish 770 kilos per day, which he finds restrictive.
Other restrictions are that I cannot fish on Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays, and I can only fish for twelve days in a month, during the four months that coastal fishing is in season, in May, June, July, and August.
In my opinion, sailors should choose their fishing days based on the weather and nothing else.
This unnecessary pressure is on people to rush instead of having 48 days over the whole summer and being able to choose at will.
The regional division might as well go my way, and coastal places that are well situated near fishing grounds should get to enjoy that," says Axel, who mostly draws cod from the briny sea on his coastal fishing trips, but also a bit of haddock and the occasional other species come along.
Axel works over the winter with his university studies at the preschool Núpur in Kópavogur.
"I think we are not many sailors who work in the country's preschools," says Axel proudly and adds that he had only intended to work temporarily at the preschool.
"I got stuck there because I think this is an awesome job."
I hope that the psychology studies will be useful for me at the kindergarten level in the future," says Axel, who is also far along in his business studies.
