Now COVID-19 has broken through like a powerful wave," Reuters quotes Elbert Huang, director of the Center for Chronic Disease Research and Policy at the University of Chicago.
Diabetes is more common among black people and those of South American descent, who have also been harder hit by the coronavirus.
One of the best defenses for those with diabetes type 2 is to keep the disease under control with exercise, a healthy diet, and the assistance of healthcare professionals.
The coronavirus pandemic, however, has made it difficult for many to maintain a routine.
Then, the high cost of insulin has forced some to continue going to work and thus risk being exposed to the virus.
Reuters points out that the US authorities had to be aware of the danger that those with type 2 diabetes could pose from the virus.
When the SARS coronavirus epidemic occurred in 2003, over 20% of those with the disease were at risk, and during the swine flu pandemic in 2009, this group was three times more likely to need hospitalization.
When MERS emerged in 2012, one study showed that 60% of those who died or were admitted to intensive care had diabetes.
