Ambassador-free for five years from 2009
Jeffrey Gunter Ross, the American ambassador to Iceland, is in the media spotlight after CBS reported this morning that he wanted an armed bodyguard because he feared for his life.
However, it has not been without difficulty for the President of the United States to appoint an ambassador here in Iceland.
Since Carol Van Voorst stepped down from the position of the United States Ambassador in April 2009, the country has been without an ambassador for a total of 62 months, more than five years.
Van Voorst resigned from office under peculiar circumstances, but the investigative program Kastljós reported in 2009 that she was supposed to receive the Order of the Falcon.
On the way to a farewell meeting with the President of Iceland, she received a phone call from the Presidential Office stating that she would not be awarded the honor.
After she disappeared from Iceland, she taught international relations at the Army War College.
Sixteen months passed until Van Voorst's successor came to work in September 2010.
To some extent, it can be attributed to the fact that Robert S. Connan had been appointed as an ambassador but then changed his mind.
After a long search, Louis Ariega, who had worked in the foreign service for decades, finally took the job.
He then retired in the fall of 2013 and assumed the position of ambassador to Guatemala.
Then another period without an ambassador began.
Robert Barber received the approval of the United States Congress in January 2015 and took office shortly thereafter, but by then no ambassador had been in place for 13 months.
Barber was a political appointee and not a diplomat; instead, he had worked as a lawyer and supported Barack Obama's election fund.
He resigned from his post as soon as Donald Trump assumed the presidency, on January 20, 2017, as is customary with politically appointed ambassadors.
The Trump administration took an unusually long time to appoint both ambassadors and high-ranking officials in the Washington bureaucracy.
Two years passed until the United States Congress summoned Jeffrey Ross Gunter to its meeting to thoroughly question him and subsequently confirm him as the ambassador to Iceland.
In his testimony to the parliament, he said that he had never been to Iceland but often to Western Europe, and that his wife, who is deceased, had been of Dutch descent.
Gunter is a political appointee who previously worked as a dermatologist in California and has been prominent in the Republican Jewish Coalition in the Republican Party.
Casino owner Sheldon Adelson founded the organization, and Adelson is an ardent supporter of Donald Trump.
Gunter arrived for work in Iceland in May 2019, but at that time no ambassador had been in the country since early in 2017, for two years and four months, which is the longest such instance on record in this country.
The reason is both how long Trump's administration took to nominate people to key positions and that in recent years, the work of the US Congress has been very protracted, including confirming ambassadors to their posts.
