Gerðar's mosaic work finally gets to be fully appreciated
In front of the Customs House in Reykjavik is a large and deep hole.
Inside there are men with orange helmets.
There is also a big dig.
And more small work machines.
The street is closed to traffic.
But the sidewalk is narrow and now many people pause and admire the artwork made of millions of mosaic tiles — as if they have never seen it before.
Maybe they have never seen it before.
At least not considered it worth their while.
The work has so far been somewhat hidden, directly in front of it there were parking spaces that were always busy.
People stopped there, quickly locked the car and then dashed off to run their errands in the downtown area.
"Lively and diverse public spaces" and "an attractive urban character" are guiding principles in the redevelopment of Tryggvagata which is currently underway.
The objective is to beautify the area and allow the mosaic work of Gerður Helgadóttir on the Customs House to be more visible.
In front of the work, there will be a plaza, and since the area is well-oriented to the sun, it is considered suitable as a resting area for passersby.
The artwork will be lit up and now the material can be better appreciated than before on this 142 square meter surface.
In the area, there will also be small "mist diffusers," a sort of water sculpture, that offer play and give the area a certain sense of mystery.
The renovations are described in this manner by the City of Reykjavik, which is carrying out the works in collaboration with Veitur.
The water supply, heating supply, and electrical supply systems will be renovated.
Many of them have reached their years, but the sewer and cold water pipes are from the year 1925 and have therefore served the residents and businesses in the downtown area for almost a century.
When the street is reopened after the completion of construction, cars can drive on it again.
However, it will become a one-way street and at the same time a calmer and more accessible space will be created for pedestrians.
In the information about the Customs House on the Customs Director's website, it is stated that the building was put into use in 1971 and its architect was Gísli Halldórsson.
Because the harbor shed extended through the house, a 250 square meter windowless wall surface facing the street was formed.
The building committee and architect agreed that such a surface would have a negative impact on the overall streetscape, unless special measures were taken to embellish the appearance of the house.
The parties therefore agreed to plan on erecting a permanent piece of art there.
At that time, a lot of talk was about Gerður Helgadóttir, the artist, the summary says.
She had worked extensively on mosaic artworks in Germany and elsewhere.
It was decided to first contact her before it would be decided whether a competition would be held for the project.
Often it had been discussed that the work needed to reflect life at the harbor, since the harbor had been the lifeline of Reykjavik since it was made.
When the artist was spoken to, she immediately became fascinated by such a work.
It was agreed that she would receive drawings and other assistance before she left the country again, as she would work on the proposals abroad.
Gerdur was given the time she decided she needed, and when she returned home, she presented several proposals for discussion.
The approval was immediately given to ask her to undertake the task.
At the same time, a desire was expressed to enter into a comprehensive agreement with her and the famous art enterprise in Germany, the Oidtmann Brothers, as Gerður had long collaborated with them on the installation of famous artworks throughout Europe.
Negotiations were successful, and Gerður created the artwork during the setup of their brothers' workshop, who then took care of installing it in the Customs House.
The entire work was exceptionally well executed, both by Gerðar Helgadóttir and the Oidtmann brothers, the summary states.
It has ever since withstood the harsh Icelandic weather.
It took Gerður about two years to complete the work, which was done and installed in the years 1972 and 1973.
The artist passed away two years after the Tollhús project was completed, only 47 years old.
