Pension Funds and Long Shadows
The year 2019 was a significant anniversary year in the history of pension funds in Iceland.
Officials had indeed received a pension from the King of Denmark all the way from the 19th century, but in 1919 a pension fund for officials was established, which eventually became the pension fund for all public employees.
The foundation for the current pension funds of general wage earners was then established with comprehensive wage agreements in the labor market in 1969, where employment-related pension funds with mandatory membership and full-fledged fund accumulation from the beginning of 1970 were stipulated.
In 1974, laws were enacted based on these agreements, and the pension system continued to strengthen after that.
The pension system for wage earners was not the only radical change that the labor movement of the 20th century drove forward through its struggles for better wages and conditions.
Unemployment insurance had been obtained in a similar manner in the historic strike disputes of 1955, and the associations also gradually succeeded in advancing their demands for sick leave rights and health funds, substantial vacation rights, reduction of working hours, improvements in housing issues, and more such matters of great importance.
All these rights came at the cost of a great and strict struggle but proved, in hindsight, to be a much greater and more lasting improvement in living standards than the increase in coins in the wage packet, which immediately disappeared into the pit of inflation that characterized the period after the war and up until 1990 as many remember.
The lead-up to the establishment of general pension funds in 1969 was both long and complex.
Although it was eventually agreed that the funds would in fact be owned by the fund members, the labor movement had to agree that their boards would be appointed with representatives of employers and fund members equally.
In the years following the establishment of the funds, the demand for a majority of workers on the boards of the funds was often discussed in labor unions, but it never came to pass, and therefore we still have the unnatural situation where representatives of the fund members are not in the majority on the boards of the funds.
Article 36 of Act No. 129/1997 on mandatory insurance of pension rights and the operation of pension funds discusses the investment strategies of the funds.
The first clause states that "a pension fund shall have the interests of fund members as its guiding principle."
Also, paragraph 5 states: "A pension fund shall establish ethical guidelines for its investments."
In the shareholders' policy of the Commercial Employees' Pension Fund, among other provisions, following the aforementioned legal provisions:
The pension fund is a signatory to the United Nations (UN PRI) Principles for Responsible Investment, along with many of the largest pension funds and institutional investors from across the Atlantic and in Europe.
In the rules, it is discussed how an emphasis on environmental and social issues, as well as good corporate governance, can contribute to improved investment performance of securities portfolios.
Thus the interests of investors and the goals of society at large go hand in hand.
LV believes it is important that companies, especially those listed on the stock market, establish a public policy on: adhering to good governance, working conditions, social responsibility, and environmental issues.
The pension fund Gildi, which is among the largest funds in the country, has established a "policy on responsible investments" and therein are provisions of a similar nature.
This is all revisited here as an introduction to the latest buzzword in Icelandic, "shadow governance".
Where the term is new in the language, it’s not expected that it has been fully defined, but what seems to be the "most accepted" definition now is: Shadow governance is when a union leader announces in the media that they intend to send recommendations or directives to the union’s representatives on the pension fund board on how they should position themselves on a specific issue.
If they do not follow the recommendations, they will be asked to step down from the board at the first opportunity.
If the leader does not take this to the media and does not talk about resignation, then it is however not "shadow governance," as such communications between people are of course always in the financial world as elsewhere.
I leave it to the reader to ponder which path they find "more ominous."
Particularly, there are two men who have tried to shape this definition when this is written, on the morning of Saturday, July 25, 2020.
Those are Hörður Ægisson, a journalist at Fréttablaðið, and Ásgeir Jónsson, the governor of the Central Bank.
The reason for both was after Bogi Nils Bogason, CEO of Icelandair, announced his intention to terminate the company's contracts with flight attendants and cabin crew (lay them off), and Ragnar Þór Ingólfsson, chairman of the Reykjavik Commercial Workers' Union, then sent out recommendations to the union's representatives on the board of the Commercial Workers' Pension Fund not to support the fund's potential purchase of shares in the company, otherwise they might be asked to step down.
Some time later, Bogi Nils retracted his decision and subsequently, Ragnar Þór followed suit with his recommendations, which were of course based on Bogi's decision.
Nevertheless, Hörður and Ásgeir saw reason to expound on the matter in the Friday edition of Fréttablaðið with grandiose words about shadow governance, legal violations, and a strong need for changes in legislation.
There, a small mound truly had to overturn a heavy load although the blessed mound had been in subjunctive mood, and moreover, had been quickly dried out.
As the matter is important, let us consider the substance itself in the end.
I have previously outlined the points in the pension fund law that relate to this matter.
The essence of this is that fund managers must protect the interests of the fund members and maintain ethical standards in investments, and these matters are further elaborated in the regulations of both Gildi and the Commerce Employees' Pension Fund, as I mentioned.
Pension funds, however, should NOT focus solely on short-term profitability objectives in their investments.
Such a policy would indeed be extremely dangerous and one does not have to look far for examples of this in the past, where large loans from banks and funds have flowed to immoral adventurers and environmental vandals, with disastrous consequences.
The CEO of Icelandair was obviously on thin ice when he considered wiping out an entire group of employees, thereby significantly reducing the goodwill the company had enjoyed in the Icelandic market and weakening its position with investors.
Fortunately, he realized his mistake and retracted it.
Time will reveal whether it suffices for the pension funds' investment in the company to be considered responsible towards the members in the end.
