One of the three who were diagnosed with Covid-19 in the country yesterday came to the country from a Baltic state on the 15th of July last, about a week and a half ago.
He is an Icelander who is not permanently residing here and therefore did not receive clear instructions about maintaining so-called border screening and testing upon arrival in the country, and to have another test taken a few days after arrival.
He received a negative result from the screening at the border.
"But he is in Icelandic society and should really go into that measure," says Kamilla Jósepsdóttir, a specialist in the field of infection prevention at the Directorate of Health and the deputy chief epidemiologist while he is on summer vacation, in a conversation with Fréttablaðið today.
"He used the English registration form and there is no obligation to register the national ID number, and if the national ID number is not registered, then you are not automatically summoned for the second sample."
She says that the man could have used the English registration form because he is actually residing abroad, but due to his network of connections in the country as an Icelander, he should have rather used the Icelandic one.
He did not realize this, however.
"When the national identification number is not registered, you need to take the initiative to come for the second sampling."
Neither he nor his employer seem to have realized that it was the right way," says Kamilla.
"So it is clear that we need to enhance the information dissemination about this while we find some way to implement an automated notification system even though Icelanders do not register their social security number."
Or to somehow make it more obvious who the participants in the Icelandic community are in the registration system," she explains.
Fortunately, the individual had limited contact with others upon arrival in the country, although he is defined as a participant in Icelandic society, being an Icelander.
Only six have been sent into quarantine after he was diagnosed yesterday, and these six were all in contact with him.
They have yet to go for sampling, but two of them have started showing symptoms of Covid-19 infection.
The man received a negative result from his sample collection at the border on July 15th.
Kamilla says it is likely that he was so recently infected with the virus that it could not yet be detected in him when the sample was taken at the border.
She does not want to rule out the possibility that the man was infected here in Iceland and did not bring the virus with him to the country.
"It is not entirely possible to assert that this is definitely an imported infection because it has been so long since he came to the country that he could have been exposed here just like these two who have caused a bit of a stir in connection with the sports events."
She says, however, that it's very unlikely because of how few people the man interacted with here.
"It is actually very unlikely," says Kamilla, but notes that it cannot be ruled out until deCODE Genetics has finished sequencing the virus in the person.
"If we get a virus strain that has not been seen here before, then it is almost certain that he has brought it into the country."
