An entire apartment building crumbles down in the best location in the city.
Romanian workers live for free at Dunhaga 18–20.
While owners seek building permits for renovations, their application has been winding through the system for going on three years.
In one of the oldest, greenest and most expensive districts of Reykjavik city stands a substantial multi-story building on three floors.
On the ground floor of the house is about 600 square meters of retail space.
Behind the house are doors to two stairwells, each containing four rather substantial apartments.
They range from 93–130 square meters, although most are over 100.
The house has a considerable history to contain.
It was built in 1959 and has among other things housed a video rental, Skóstofan, the dairy shop of Mjólkursamsalan, Jói the gunsmith, a fish market and most recently Háskólaprent.
The house, to put it mildly, has seen better days.
The house now lies heavily damaged, as can be seen in the accompanying pictures.
The owner of the house is D18 ehf.
According to the company registry, among others, the owners of D18 ehf. are Magnús Magnússon and Guðrún Helga Lárusdóttir.
Magnús led the group of owners of Borgun and was the representative of the holding company of Borgun.
Among the owners of the holding company Borgun is Stálskip ehf.
Steelship Ltd. is the investment company of Guðrún Helga Lárusdóttir and her children.
Guðrún is also the owner of a one-third share in D18 ehf.
Guðrún and her husband, Ágúst Guðmundur Sigurðsson, once operated the fishing company Stálskip.
D18 Ltd. bought the house in the summer of 2009 and has therefore barely been maintained since then.
Neighbors say that the condition of the house has steadily deteriorated since then, especially in recent years.
On the neighborhood's Facebook page, one resident says the house has "not been particularly lively in recent years."
There may be a factor that for several years, the owners have been seeking to alter the house and the land.
Other neighbors say the house has not been alright for a long time.
"It's long overdue to do something proper with this spot and it's annoying that it has been delayed like this."
He also says that he is angry with the owners of the house for not having pushed themselves to finish this, to find some common ground with the neighbors of the house and to stop this “legal charade.”
"Just do this in consultation with the surrounding community so that it can be expedited and completed."
The "legal quagmire" the resident refers to is the planning process for the site which has been underway at least since 2017.
Then, the owners of Dunhagi 18 and 20 applied for permission to construct a floor on top of the existing apartment building, and behind the house, a new elevator shaft and an extension of one floor plus a basement.
The building permit granted for that project was appealed to the Environmental and Resource Affairs Appeals Committee, and the committee invalidated it as the project was not based on a detailed plan, and the neighborhood notification was not satisfactory.
The City of Reykjavik then initiated a detailed planning process, which was completed with an announcement in the Official Gazette in July of the previous year.
The arrangement was also appealed and the committee revoked it in March 2020.
At this point, nearly three years had passed since the original application for a building permit and the owners of the house at the starting square.
The house had by this time deteriorated significantly and the neighbors had begun to get tired.
When DV asked the neighbors about the condition of the house and the neighbors' reactions, the answers varied.
Some understood the intentions of the house owners, others not at all.
Others directed their anger towards the city, others did not.
Others were just angry but not necessarily at anyone in particular.
Yet others called the parking spaces a bone of contention, but neighbors have utilized the unused parking spaces at Dunhaga 18–20 for their vehicles.
One complainant in the case said they were tired of the bureaucracy:
"That we have to go through the process three times is absolutely incredible."
"It's like the City of Reykjavik doesn't know how to read."
Today the house stands empty, abandoned, and is neglected.
A memorial to the city administration's efficient governance and the noble intentions of the owner and the years of work by those who are now at the starting square.
When the journalist arrived at Dunhaga 18, he was met with wide-open doors and piles of rubbish.
A PlayStation console and a recent-model television lay among other rubbish on the ground — victims of the Icelandic summer rain.
The door was open to the old office of University Press, and from the smell of urine, there were quite a few cats inside.
It is clear that someone has made themselves at home in one corner, but no one is visible.
Piles of sofas and beds and a few shelves of geological pages, which were no doubt intended to become a book, were on display.
The stairwells of the apartment building were also open and there was life in both of them.
A journalist was so lucky to come across a resident of one of them.
There were Romanians boiling a potato dish for dinner and they invited a reporter inside.
The Romanians work for the staffing agency Ztrongforce ehf.
They have been there for some time and sources of DV claim that the company has not paid anything for the housing except for heating and electricity.
Due to the condition of the house, it is not considered justifiable to collect rent.
Judging by the piles of mail in the lobby of the building, it's clear that a number of foreign workers have lived there over the past few months.
The operation of temp agencies has not been unaffected by the Covid-19 situation, with the contraction in tourism leading to a contraction in the construction industry, and these two sectors have been the most diligent in utilizing the services of temp agencies.
Nevertheless, the residents of Dunhaga 18 seemed to have plenty to do, and the work coveralls and mittens hung in the communal area to dry after a long day of work in the rain.
It should be noted that despite the wretched condition of the house, the apartment that the boys shared seemed to be fairly well maintained.
When the journalist waved goodbye to the Romanian boys, the irony suddenly became clear to him: In the best location in Reykjavik stands a 1,500 square meter property, run down.
The owners want to improve the house and neighbors want better conditions but disagree on the definition of "improvement".
Between sits the city's planning division at the starting square, a victim of endless appeal routes and complaint options in the planning process and the sluggish resolution of the Environmental and Natural Resources Complaints Committee.
In the house, Romanian workers live, perhaps precisely those who will work on improving the condition when the Icelanders stop quarreling.
The article originally appeared in the DV weekend paper on July 17th.
