Heading into a hundred days until the election
There are a hundred days left until Americans go to the polls and elect a president for four years.
Donald Trump is seeking reelection, but he has a steep hill to climb.
Joe Biden, the presumptive Democratic nominee, has a significant national lead over Trump, according to polls.
According to a new AP news agency survey, a record number of Americans believe that the nation is on the wrong track.
Trump's response to the new coronavirus pandemic is also very unpopular, and moreover, more Americans than before believe that the president has handled economic matters poorly.
More specifically, only two out of every ten Americans say that the United States is on the right track.
32 percent say they support Trump's response to the pandemic, and 48 percent say he has handled economic matters well.
In March, the percentage was 56 percent and in January, it was 67 percent.
According to the FiveThirtyEight average, Biden's national support is 49.9 percent while Trump's support is 41.9 percent.
Trump himself has tried to shift attention from his performance regarding the pandemic to Biden, pushing so-called cultural conflicts and advocating policies related to law and order.
Biden's campaign, however, is very focused on keeping the attention on Trump and believes there is a high probability of victory if the election truly revolves around how Trump has performed in office over the past four years.
Trump's unpopularity also seems likely to affect the Republican senators, and those at the forefront fear that the Democrats could even gain a majority in the US Senate, which has until now seemed very unlikely.
Politico recently reported that if the current support for parties and candidates remains the same, the Republican Party would suffer its worst defeat in decades.
Suburbs proved to be particularly bad for the party in the 2016 parliamentary elections, and now it seems that this trend will continue.
In recent days, Trump has tried to scare suburban residents into following him, among other things, by saying that if Biden becomes president, he will ruin the suburbs of the United States and encourage racial strife.
Among other things, Trump has repealed a regulation from the time of Barack Obama in the White House that was intended to increase diversity in the suburbs.
Then he encouraged the "housewives" of the suburbs of the United States to read an article by the former assistant governor of New York, in which she argued that Biden would destroy the suburbs of the United States, and Trump agreed with that.
"Biden will destroy your neighborhoods and the American dream."
I will preserve it, and even make it better!" said the president.
Residents of the suburbs of the United States are an ever-growing group of voters.
According to NPR, they are about half of all voters in the United States.
Since George W. Bush was re-elected in 2004, the candidate who has received the majority of votes from this group has become president.
Except in the year 2012 when Mitt Romney received the majority of votes from this group but lost to Barack Obama.
Opinion polls have shown that although Trump secured a narrow majority in the suburbs in 2016, his support there has significantly decreased.
Though it varies between polls, Biden has recently measured about a fifteen-percentage point lead over Trump in the predictions.
Regis Philbin has passed away
American television host Regis Philbin has passed away, aged 88.
Philbin worked as an actor, host, presenter, and singer for about six decades.
He is best known for hosting the popular talk show Live! with Regis from 1988 to 2011 alongside Kathie Lee Gifford and later Kelly Ripa.
Then he has directed episodes of shows such as Who Wants to Be a Millionaire and America's Got Talent.
According to Guinness World Records, Philbin is the individual who has spent the most hours on American television, and he has received recognition for this.
He received six Emmy Awards in his career and was nominated a total of 37 times.
It is stated in a declaration from his family that Philbin died of natural causes.
A number of colleagues, friends, and admirers have remembered him on social media in the last 24 hours.
Will the Olympic flame be the light at the end of the tunnel?
After the final decision had been made to postpone the Olympic Games, an event that until now only world wars had interrupted, the president of the International Olympic Committee said that the famed Olympic flame would be "the light at the end of the tunnel," presumably referring to the global coronavirus pandemic that the world is currently navigating together.
Outstanding individuals have an extra year to prepare and Japanese authorities bear the cost of the delay.
Everyone keeps their head though a lot is at stake.
When it was announced that Tokyo in Japan would be the venue for this year's Olympic Games, the Japanese representatives' rejoicing was genuine.
They cried and laughed in turns because Tokyo had applied to host the 2016 games but was that time defeated by Rio in Brazil.
This time Tokyo City and Japan were to bathe in the world's attention.
The games were supposed to take place from July 24th to August 9th but have been postponed for a year and will instead start on July 23rd, 2021, and end on August 8th.
If it is not possible to hold the games then, if the coronavirus is still too much of a threat, the games will be canceled.
No one really wants to think that thought through to the end.
The Olympic Games are no ordinary sports competition.
Nothing is spared, the show must always be spectacular and strives to outdo the last performance.
The choice of a city for the Olympic Games is based on the evaluation committee's assessment of the cities' presentations.
The more spectacular the presentation — the greater the chance of winning the prize.
Tokyo spent 150 million dollars in trying to host the 2016 Olympic Games, which is equivalent to over 20 billion kroner.
For the second time, when applying for the 2020 Games, 75 million dollars, about ten billion krona, were put into the promotion.
In 2013, when it was decided that Tokyo would host the games this year, Japanese authorities had already spent an amount equivalent to 30 billion krona on the project.
Yet that amount is just a drop in the ocean compared to the cost of constructing an Olympic Village, stadiums, and generally strengthening the country's infrastructure to handle such an event, preparing for it, and hosting the games themselves.
Organizers in Japan have said that the Tokyo Olympics, which were supposed to be underway these days but have been postponed for one year due to the coronavirus, would have cost 12.6 billion dollars.
In a report from the national auditor in Japan that was released at the end of last year, it was revealed that the cost was nearly double that figure.
It will probably not be possible to fully assess the cost of postponing the games, but it has been estimated that it could cost between two to six billion dollars in addition to the original cost.
The total cost for the Japanese Olympic Committee and Japanese taxpayers could therefore run in the range of 15 to 30 billion dollars.
There are such high figures that all the tax revenues of the Icelandic state would only suffice for just under half an Olympic Games, based on the lowest possible cost.
The Olympic Games are an event of such magnitude that they often become the subject of economists, who try to scrutinize the numbers and examine the benefits and gains of the games.
In a nutshell, quite a few people seem to have come to the conclusion that the impact of the Olympic Games is less than positive for the economies of the cities that host them.
Short-term effects are some, for example, job opportunities increase substantially for a short period, but over the long-term, cities often end up with a burden of debt and the threateningly high operational costs of underused facilities.
Rio in Brazil is left with significant debts due to the 2016 games and has had trouble financing the maintenance of all the large sports facilities that were built for the games.
A close look has been taken at the figures following the 2012 London Games and it has been revealed that only 10 percent of those who received employment related to the Olympic Games in the city were unemployed before.
It means that there were no new jobs except to a small extent.
Generally, cities have not fared well financially from hosting the Olympic Games due to the overwhelming cost associated with the infrastructure built for the games.
However, the benefit is often considered to be in the increased flow of tourists who want to visit the Olympic cities following the games, although there is great uncertainty about this regarding the 2021 games.
It is also uncertain whether it will be possible to accommodate all the spectators who usually attend the games.
The main thing, however, is the honor that the cities receive by being chosen, but it is difficult to quantify in terms of money.
Because despite the enormous expense, it can also be said that the joy that the games bring is not such that it can be priced.
But although the show is often grandiose and no expense is spared, this is obviously not just about money.
It is the sports heroes who are in the forefront.
For some athletes, it's actually just a welcome opportunity to postpone the games.
The Australian modern pentathlete and gold medalist in her event at the last Olympic Games, Chloe Esposito, is, for instance, pregnant and would have been far from ready to compete this summer but she is hopeful to be in competitive shape for the 2021 games.
She is therefore among those athletes who are just rather pleased with the postponement, for understandable reasons.
For the athletes who intended to retire after this year's games, if they had been held at the right time, the postponement of the games means that in some cases they will quit competing before the games take place.
Simply do not trust their body to go through another year of intense training.
Few athletes managed to endear themselves as thoroughly to the hearts of spectators at the Rio 2016 Olympics as gymnastics star Simone Biles.
She came home with four gold medals around her neck and one bronze.
Biles has attended several interviews in her home country, the United States, recently to discuss the Olympic Games.
She is aiming for the 2021 games but she is not necessarily sure that she will still be at the top in next year's games, especially since she will be 24 years old by then.
While it's generally not considered old age, it's on the higher side for a top-tier female gymnast.
"This is a sensitive issue," says Biles, but still smiles in a different direction in an interview that was published on the Olympic Committee's Instagram page when asked whether she intends to go as far in the 2021 games as she did in Rio 2016.
"I simply do not know if I will still be at the top after another year of training," says Biles.
She has previously talked about how her body cannot handle the stress associated with gymnastics training much longer.
Nevertheless, she trains diligently for the 2021 Olympic Games.
Biles admits that it was an uncomfortable feeling having to suddenly stop practicing when the pandemic was at its peak and the gymnastics hall was closed.
No exceptions were made for Biles any more than for others while all sports facilities were closed for seven weeks.
All her Olympic gold couldn't buy her any access beyond the others; she had to find various ways to keep fit just like everyone else.
The basic form is certainly a bit better than most people's.
We have a tight schedule now.
It was difficult to start practicing again after the gym reopened.
We started slowly but are now back to full speed and I will gradually increase the workouts as the year progresses.
We obviously don't know exactly how these games will turn out or whether they will be held, but we still practice assuming that they will be; we can't do otherwise.
"I have put too much effort into the sport to give it up now," says Biles.
Like her and others, there is a doubt or perhaps rather an awareness that the situation might arise that the games will not be held at all in 2021.
Predicting it, however, is hopeless.
No one can know what the situation with the coronavirus pandemic will be like in July 2021 and there is nothing else to do but prepare for the Olympics assuming that they will be held that year.
Perhaps the Olympic Flame will be the light at the end of the Covid-tunnel.
Postponed wedding due to epidemic
Modern Family actress Sarah Hyland has decided to postpone her wedding due to the coronavirus.
She was supposed to marry former Bachelorette contestant Wells Adams this summer.
"I think there are other more important things to think about right now," said the actress in a conversation with People.
"We definitely want to get married sometime and have the dream wedding with all those who are dear to us in attendance."
But we decided to postpone it and focus on what's important right now, which is to help share information about the importance of wearing masks and staying at home.
I am more focused on world affairs than on wedding matters these days.
There is a lot going on and we should focus our attention on what is happening in the world.
